1. Purpose and Scope
This assessment evaluates the EBS platform’s readiness to onboard new lines of business. It is structured as a pre-audit self-assessment aligned to enterprise governance standards (COBIT 2019) and designed to surface gaps before an external review.
The assessment evaluates platform capability across six pillars: governance, data, processing, integration, security, and operational observability. Each question targets a specific readiness risk with a defined objective and signal.
Scope: EBS Enrollment System — React UI, Java Spring Boot backend on OpenShift, Kafka event publishing, integrations with Sales (inbound), Billing (outbound), Communications (outbound), and EB Compute (data payload).
2. How to Use This Framework
This is not a survey. Each pillar is a 30–45 minute structured conversation with the 2–3 people who own the answers. One person asks, one answers, one captures.
Reading the Columns
Question — What is being asked. Read as written. Use the Objective if clarification is needed.
Objective — What this question is really determining. Removes interpretation ambiguity. External auditors use this to validate responses address the actual intent.
Signal — Answer spectrum from healthy (left) to concerning (right). Instant directional read without a scoring rubric.
Rating — Green (strong) | Yellow (partial) | Red (gap) | N/A (owned elsewhere — note which team).
Evidence / Artifact Reference — The specific artifact, tool, or process that supports the rating. Confluence page, Jira epic, Git repo, dashboard link, ADR, RBAC policy, runbook. “Fully implemented” without evidence is a claim, not a finding.
Respondent — Name and role of the person who provided the answer. This establishes accountability and allows the external auditor to follow up if needed.
Notes / Remediation — For Yellow/Red: what the gap is, planned remediation, target date, and owner. For N/A: which team owns this area and their audit reference if available.
