4. Pillar 0 — Onboarding Governance
“Do we even have a front door for new business?”
Before assessing platform capability, this pillar confirms whether a governed process exists for new LOB intake. Without governance, capability assessments are ad hoc and non-repeatable.
#
Question
Objective
Signal
Rating
Evidence / Artifact Reference
Respondent
Notes / Remediation
0.1
Is there a defined intake process for evaluating a new LOB against the platform?
Confirm a repeatable, documented process exists for new LOB onboarding requests — not ad hoc conversations that vary by who you ask.
Repeatable process vs. ad hoc








0.2
Are there go/no-go criteria for when the platform can absorb a new LOB vs. when custom build is needed?
Validate that explicit criteria exist to determine platform fit — preventing misaligned business from being forced into the platform.
Defined criteria vs. gut feel








0.3
Is there a single owner accountable for platform readiness decisions?
Confirm a named individual or role owns the readiness decision with clear escalation path and accountability.
Named owner vs. shared ambiguity









Finding threshold: If there is no front door, every onboarding is a fire drill. This is a governance finding that affects every subsequent pillar.

5. Pillar 1 — Data Model
“Can our data model represent this new business without surgery?”
The data model is the foundation. If the hierarchy and canonical definitions cannot accommodate the new LOB, no amount of application-layer flexibility compensates.
#
Question
Objective
Signal
Rating
Evidence / Artifact Reference
Respondent
Notes / Remediation
1.1
Can the current group / division / member hierarchy support this LOB?
Determine whether foundational data structures can represent the new business without schema redesign. If the hierarchy breaks, everything above it breaks.
Schema reuse vs. redesign








1.2
Can onboarding be config-driven (new LOB without code changes)?
Evaluate whether new business activates through configuration (reference data, flags, rules) rather than code deployments — the key indicator of platform scalability.
Config-driven vs. code change








1.3
Is there a documented data dictionary or canonical model a new LOB team can reference independently?
Confirm a new team can understand the data model without relying on verbal knowledge transfer from existing members.
Self-service vs. tribal knowledge









Finding threshold: If a new team cannot understand the data model without calling three people, the platform is not self-service ready.

6. Pillar 2 — Processing & Workflow
“Can our engine run this new business or does it need a new engine?”
Processing readiness determines whether onboarding is a configuration exercise (weeks) or a development project (months). The distinction between reuse and rebuild drives timeline and cost.
#
Question
