2.1
Does this LOB follow existing transaction types (add / change / term / renew)?
Determine whether the new business fits the existing processing taxonomy so workflow orchestration can be reused.
Reuse vs. redesign








2.2
Will processing be systematic or manual heavy?
Assess operational sustainability. Manual-heavy processing introduces human error and limits throughput — it does not scale with additional LOBs.
Automated vs. manual risk








2.3
Do current services support this logic or do we need new ones?
Evaluate service layer reuse. Parameter-level changes = fast onboarding. New service design and build = project-level effort and risk.
Tweaks vs. rebuild








2.4
Can new workflow variations be tested in isolation without impacting existing LOBs?
Confirm the platform supports isolated testing of new business logic without creating production risk for existing lines of business.
Isolated vs. shared risk









Finding threshold: If we cannot test a new LOB without holding our breath about existing ones, that is an architecture-level finding.

7. Pillar 3 — Integration & Downstream
“Can the systems around us consume what we produce for this new business?”
Platform readiness is meaningless if downstream consumers break. Integration stability is the highest-risk area during onboarding because it crosses team and system boundaries.
